Given a Quaternion created as such:

```
float heading = 90f;
Quaternion q = new Quaternion();
q.set(Vector3.Z, heading);
```

I would expect the following code:

```
float _rot = q.getRollRad();
// _rot == 0f
```

To have the same result as the following, but it does not:

```
Vector3 _bearing = new Vector3();  
_bearing.set(1f, 0f, 0f);
movement.orientation.transform(_bearing);
float _rot = (float) Math.atan2(_bearing.y, _bearing.x);
// _rot == 1.5707963
```

Similarly, using a heading of `270f` results in `getRollRad() == -6.2831855`. Reasonable values are returned for other initial values of `heading`.

As a side note, would a pull request to increase `MathUtils`' atan2 LUT precision be looked at? I've had to fall back to using Java's regular `Math.atan2`  due to its imprecision.

Hi, using Gdx.input.justTouched() on iOS will recognize only the first touch, all other touchs (second finger & co.) will not be recognized.

An example:

```
for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    if(Gdx.input.isTouched(i)) {
        // This is recognized correctly for all the fingers
        if(Gdx.input.justTouched()) {
            // This is true only with the first finger, if i am keep touching the screen with the first finger and i touch antoher point of the screen with another finger is not recognized
        }
    }
}
```

On Android is working correctly for all the touch/fingers.

